SIMPLE: singular
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Singular
<hw>Sin"gu*lar</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧"g⟦usl⟧*l⟦etil⟧r)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>singuler</ets>, F. <ets>singulier</ets>,
fr. L. <ets>singularius</ets>, <ets>singularis</ets>, fr.
<ets>singulus</ets> single. See <er>Single</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Separate or apart from others; single; distinct.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And God forbid that all a company⟦br⟧
Should rue a <qex>singular</qex> man's folly.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Engaged in by only one on a side; single.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To try the matter thus together in a <qex>singular</qex>
combat.</q> <rj><qau>Holinshed.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>Existing by itself; single;
individual.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The idea which represents one . . . determinate thing, is called a
<qex>singular</qex> idea, whether simple, complex, or compound.</q>
<rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Each; individual; <as>as, to convey
several parcels of land, all and <ex>singular</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Denoting one person or thing;
<as>as, the <ex>singular</ex> number</as>; -- opposed to
<contr>dual</contr> and <ant>plural</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Standing by itself; out of the ordinary course;
unusual; uncommon; strange; <as>as, a <ex>singular</ex>
phenomenon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So <qex>singular</qex> a sadness⟦br⟧
Must have a cause as strange as the effect.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Distinguished as existing in a very high degree;
rarely equaled; eminent; extraordinary; exceptional; <as>as, a man of
<ex>singular</ex> gravity or attainments</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Departing from general usage or expectations; odd;
whimsical; -- often implying disapproval or censure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His zeal⟦br⟧
None seconded, as out of season judged,⟦br⟧
Or <qex>singular</qex> and rash.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To be <qex>singular</qex> in anything that is wise and worthy, is
not a disparagement, but a praise.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Being alone; belonging to, or being, that of which
there is but one; unique.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These busts of the emperors and empresses are all very scarce, and
some of them almost <qex>singular</qex> in their kind.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Singular point in a curve</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>,
<cd>a point at which the curve possesses some peculiar properties not
possessed by other points of the curve, as a cusp point, or a multiple
point.</cd> -- <col><b>Singular proposition</b></col>
<fld>(Logic)</fld>, <cd>a proposition having as its subject a singular
term, or a common term limited to an individual by means of a singular
sign.</cd> <au>Whately.</au> -- <col><b>Singular succession</b></col>
<fld>(Civil Law)</fld>, <cd>division among individual successors, as
distinguished from <xex>universal succession</xex>, by which an estate
descended in intestacy to the heirs in mass.</cd> -- <col><b>Singular
term</b></col> <fld>(Logic)</fld>, <cd>a term which represents or stands
for a single individual.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Unexampled; unprecedented; eminent;
extraordinary; remarkable; uncommon; rare; unusual; peculiar; strange;
odd; eccentric; fantastic.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Singular</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Singular
<hw>Sin"gu*lar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An individual
instance; a particular.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Dr. H.
More.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gram)</fld> <def>The singular number, or the number
denoting one person or thing; a word in the singular number.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Singularist</ent>⟦br⟧
